  "response": "Let me explain the scenarios involving neutral grounding and zero sequence components during a line-to-ground fault:\n\nWhen Neutral is Not Grounded (Ungrounded System):\n\n1. During a line-to-ground fault:\n- Potential on healthy phases rises to line-to-line voltage\n- Fault current may be very small or negligible\n- System continues to operate\n- High risk of transient overvoltages\n- Increased potential for insulation breakdown\n- Difficult to locate the fault\n\nZero Sequence Component Behavior:\n\n1. When Zero Sequence Components Cannot Flow:\n- Symmetrical fault conditions\n- No ground fault current path\n- Fault detection becomes challenging\n- Protective relays may not operate\n- Potential for sustained fault conditions\n- System stability might be compromised\n\nConsequences:\n- Increased electrical stress\n- Potential equipment damage\n- Reduced system protection effectiveness\n- Higher risk of cascading failures\n\nRecommended Practices:\n- Implement proper grounding techniques\n- Use ground fault detection mechanisms\n- Establish clear zero sequence current paths\n- Regular system monitoring and maintenance\n\nThese scenarios highlight the importance of proper grounding and understanding sequence component behavior in electrical systems.",
